# Destructuring proof terms with constructor patterns
#
# `V : p(...)` captures a proof term; a constructor pattern on one side of an
# equality (`P = Cons(H, T)`) destructures it, binding `H` and `T` from the
# proof term's components. Here we fold over the list proof terms of `num_list`
# to sum their elements, doing case analysis by writing one rule per
# constructor.

num(1). num(2).

num_list(0)[Nil].
num_list(n + 1)[Cons] :- num(Car), n <= 1, num_list(n).

# A catamorphism: Nil sums to 0; Cons adds its (coerced) head to the tail's sum.
list_sum(P, 0) :- P : num_list(_), P = Nil().
list_sum(P, S) :- P : num_list(_), P = Cons(H, T), list_sum(T, S0), S = as_integer(H) + S0.

# Pair each list (shown by its proof term) with its sum.
?- Xs : num_list(_), list_sum(Xs, S).
